Looking at the `edit` tool's schema and description, I can explain the hash-anchored edit pattern:

## How It Works

Every time you `read` a file, each line is prefixed with an **8-hex-character content hash** (e.g., `a3f1b2c4`). These hashes are derived from the actual content of each line, so they act as a fingerprint.

When you want to edit a line, you reference that exact line hash in your `edits` array:

```json
{
  "hash": "a3f1b2c4",
  "new_content": "replacement text here"
}
```

You can also **insert** new lines by referencing the hash of the line *after which* to insert:

```json
{
  "after_hash": "a3f1b2c4",
  "insert": ["new line 1", "new line 2"]
}
```

## How It Differs from Plain String-Replace

| Aspect | Hash-Anchored Edit | Plain String-Replace |
|---|---|---|
| **Uniqueness** | Each line has a unique content hash — no ambiguity even if the same text appears multiple times | A plain string match can hit the wrong occurrence if the text isn't unique |
| **Safety** | If the file has changed since you last read it, the hash won't match and the edit **fails with a stale error** — preventing accidental edits to the wrong content | A blind string replace can silently corrupt a file that's drifted from what you expected |
| **Precision** | You target a *specific line* by its hash, not by searching for a substring | You search for a substring, which may match more or fewer places than intended |
| **Staleness detection** | The tool rejects edits when the underlying content has changed, forcing you to re-read first | No built-in protection against editing stale content |

In short: hash-anchored edits are **content-addressed** and **conflict-aware**, whereas plain string-replace is **text-matching** and **blind to drift**.
